r’s output to date, and the necessary background – personal or national, cultural or political – to enable readers to achieve a better understanding of the director’s choice of subject matter, aesthetic or formal strategies, or ideological stance. They also offer a particular reading of one or more films, in which the authors aim to situate African cinema in relation to important critical and theoretical debates. This book thus constitutes a new departure in African film studies, recognising the maturity of the field, and the need for complex yet accessible approaches to it, which move beyond the purely descriptive while refusing to get bogged down in theoretical jargon. Consequently, the volume should be of interest not only to specialists but also to the general reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszAfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszAfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPostcolonialismzAfrica. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAfrican filmmakers.  aDarrell James Roodt.  aDjibril Diop Mambety.  aFlora Gomes.  aFrancophone African cinema.  aIdrissa Ouédraogo.  aJean-Pierre Bekolo.  aMed Hondo.  aMoufida Tlatli.  aOusmane Sembene.  aPostcolonial African cinema.  aSouleymane Cissé.  aYoussef Chahine.  aauthorial tradition.1 aMurphy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilliams, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614173640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526141